flowRoot.flowPara: Presuming the necessary infrastructure is built, NETs at large scales requires that humans assume control of global biogeochemical processes. 1.5C or even 2C pathways would require CO drawdowns by 2100 greater than the entire natural land sink - i.e. all CO sequestration on Earth that is currently performed by plants. Even though we have unintentionally entered the "anthropocene", it may be hubristic to assume we can actively manage the global carbon cycle at such a scale without adverse consequences on humans and nature.

NETs dis-incentivise costly near-term mitigation, due to the expectation that carbon budgets will expand in the future. This moral hazard can be observed in two equivalent integrated assessment scenarios for meeting 2C, one of which does not allow carbon capture technologies. In the no-CCS scenario, mitigation occurs faster and deeper, reaching a gap of 9.1 GtCO by 2030. Where CCS is permitted, the lack of near-term mitigation commits future generations to a long-term dependence on NETs, with or without their consent.

If a NETs pathway to 2C is chosen, how feasible is the scale-up required? There are currently 3 BECCS plants in operation (on a demonstration, not commercial basis). From this low baseline, a surprising number of plants (50,000) have to be approved, funded, constructed and operational by 2030 - with 150,000 more by the mid-century. "Betting" on NETs therefore entails a non-trivial technological feat, involving significant economic costs, institutional compexities, and social risks.
